hook.real_world_problem:
Two problems you've hit before:

**Problem 1**: You tried to remove elements while iterating a list — ConcurrentModificationException. You needed `removeIf()` as a workaround. But `removeIf()` only works for simple conditions. What about complex removal logic that needs to check multiple things, maintain state between items, or remove by index?

**Problem 2**: Your code is full of repetitive patterns:

```java
// Find minimum:
int min = list.get(0);
for (int x : list) if (x < min) min = x;

// Sort:
Arrays.sort(arr);  // for arrays
list.sort(...);     // for lists

// Reverse:
// ??? manual loop
```

The Java Collections Framework solved both. `Iterator` lets you safely remove during iteration. `Collections` utility class has `min()`, `max()`, `sort()`, `reverse()`, `shuffle()`, `frequency()` and more — one-liners that replace your manual loops.

Today: the complete toolkit for working with collections.

concept_explanation.iterator_basics:
**Iterator** is the interface that powers all for-each loops internally. You can also use it explicitly when you need more control.

```java
List<String> names = new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList("Aisha", "Raj", "Priya"));

// For-each (internally uses Iterator)
for (String name : names) {
    System.out.println(name);
}

// Explicit Iterator
Iterator<String> it = names.iterator();
while (it.hasNext()) {
    String name = it.next();
    System.out.println(name);
}
```

**Why use explicit Iterator?** One reason: **safe removal during iteration**.

```java
Iterator<String> it = names.iterator();
while (it.hasNext()) {
    String name = it.next();
    if (name.startsWith("R")) {
        it.remove();  // SAFE — removes current element via Iterator
    }
}
// names is now [Aisha, Priya]
```

`it.remove()` removes the element that `it.next()` last returned. It's coordinated with the iterator's internal state — no ConcurrentModificationException.

**The three Iterator methods**:
- `hasNext()` — true if more elements remain
- `next()` — returns next element and advances iterator
- `remove()` — removes the element last returned by next()

**Important**: call `next()` before `remove()`. Calling `remove()` twice in a row (without `next()` in between) throws IllegalStateException.

concept_explanation.iterator_vs_removeif:
**Iterator vs removeIf** — when to use which:

```java
// removeIf: perfect for simple lambda conditions
list.removeIf(s -> s.startsWith("R"));

// Iterator: better when:
// - logic is complex (needs multiple lines)
// - you need to do something BEFORE removing
// - you need the index or other state
// - you're modifying related data structures while iterating

Iterator<Order> it = orders.iterator();
while (it.hasNext()) {
    Order order = it.next();
    if (order.isExpired()) {
        archiveLog.add(order);      // log it first
        refundAmount += order.total; // track total refund
        it.remove();                  // then remove
    }
}
```

Rule: `removeIf` for simple condition-based removal. `Iterator` when you need to do more around the removal.

concept_explanation.listiterator:
**ListIterator** extends Iterator for Lists — adds bidirectional traversal:

```java
List<String> list = new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList("A", "B", "C", "D"));
ListIterator<String> lit = list.listIterator(list.size()); // start at end

// Traverse BACKWARDS:
while (lit.hasPrevious()) {
    System.out.print(lit.previous() + " ");  // D C B A
}

// Can also set() to replace current element:
ListIterator<String> lit2 = list.listIterator();
while (lit2.hasNext()) {
    String s = lit2.next();
    lit2.set(s.toLowerCase());  // replace with lowercase
}
// list is now [a, b, c, d]
```

**ListIterator's extra methods**:
- `hasPrevious()`, `previous()` — go backwards
- `nextIndex()`, `previousIndex()` — current position
- `set(element)` — replace last returned element
- `add(element)` — insert at current position

**Common use**: transforming elements in-place (replace as you iterate — much cleaner than `list.set(i, transform(list.get(i)))` in a for loop).

concept_explanation.entrySet_iteration:
**Iterating Maps** — use `entrySet()` when you need both key and value:

```java
Map<String, Integer> scores = new HashMap<>();
scores.put("Aisha", 95); scores.put("Raj", 87); scores.put("Priya", 92);

// EFFICIENT: one access per entry
for (Map.Entry<String, Integer> entry : scores.entrySet()) {
    System.out.println(entry.getKey() + ": " + entry.getValue());
}

// INEFFICIENT: two lookups per entry (get() on each key)
for (String key : scores.keySet()) {
    System.out.println(key + ": " + scores.get(key));  // get() is extra work
}
```

`entrySet()` gives you key+value together in one object — no second lookup. For large maps, this matters. For small maps, it's just the idiomatic style.

**Modifying values during iteration** — use `entry.setValue()`:
```java
for (Map.Entry<String, Integer> entry : scores.entrySet()) {
    entry.setValue(entry.getValue() + 5);  // add 5 bonus points to everyone
}
```

**Never put/remove keys during entrySet iteration** — ConcurrentModificationException. Use a separate list of keys to update, or iterate the list after.

concept_explanation.collections_min_max_frequency:
**Finding extremes and counts**:

```java
List<Integer> scores = Arrays.asList(72, 88, 95, 65, 88, 91);

int max = Collections.max(scores);  // 95
int min = Collections.min(scores);  // 65

// With Comparator (for objects):
List<Product> products = ...;
Product cheapest = Collections.min(products);          // uses Comparable
Product priciest = Collections.max(products, Comparator.comparingDouble(Product::getPrice));

// Count occurrences:
int eighty8count = Collections.frequency(scores, 88);  // 2

// Check if two collections share NO elements:
List<String> a = Arrays.asList("cat", "dog");
List<String> b = Arrays.asList("fish", "bird");
boolean noCommon = Collections.disjoint(a, b);  // true
```

`Collections.frequency(list, element)` counts how many times element appears — uses equals().

concept_explanation.collections_unmodifiable:
**Making collections read-only** — defensive API design:

```java
class Library {
    private List<Book> books = new ArrayList<>();

    // Return unmodifiable view — callers cannot add/remove
    public List<Book> getBooks() {
        return Collections.unmodifiableList(books);
    }
}

// Caller:
List<Book> lib = library.getBooks();
lib.add(new Book(...));     // throws UnsupportedOperationException!
lib.get(0).setTitle("..."); // OK — can still modify elements themselves
```

`Collections.unmodifiableList(list)` returns a WRAPPER — any mutation attempts throw `UnsupportedOperationException`. The underlying list is unchanged but hidden behind the wrapper.

**Also available**: `unmodifiableMap()`, `unmodifiableSet()`.

**Modern alternative (Java 9+)**: `List.of(...)`, `Map.of(...)`, `Set.of(...)` — truly immutable collections that can't be modified even from inside. Prefer these for creating fixed data.

```java
List<String> fixed = List.of("Java", "Python", "Go");  // immutable
// fixed.add("Rust");  // UnsupportedOperationException
```

concept_explanation.collections_fill_copy:
**Other useful Collections methods**:

```java
List<String> list = new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList("a", "b", "c"));

// Replace all elements with one value:
Collections.fill(list, "x");   // [x, x, x]

// Copy src into dest (dest must be same size or larger):
List<String> dest = new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList("1", "2", "3"));
Collections.copy(dest, Arrays.asList("a", "b"));  // dest = [a, b, 3]

// Create a list of N copies of one element:
List<String> nines = Collections.nCopies(5, "nine");  // [nine, nine, nine, nine, nine]

// Swap two elements:
Collections.swap(list, 0, 2);  // swaps elements at index 0 and 2

// Binary search (list must be SORTED first):
List<Integer> sorted = Arrays.asList(1, 3, 5, 7, 9);
int idx = Collections.binarySearch(sorted, 5);  // returns 2
```

`binarySearch` only works correctly on **sorted** lists. If unsorted, result is undefined.

concept_explanation.streams_preview:
**Streams — a brief preview** (covered fully in Module 9):

Java 8 introduced streams as a declarative alternative to loops for processing collections:

```java
List<String> names = Arrays.asList("Aisha", "Raj", "Priya", "Vikram");

// Traditional loop:
List<String> longNames = new ArrayList<>();
for (String name : names) {
    if (name.length() > 3) longNames.add(name.toUpperCase());
}

// Stream equivalent:
List<String> longNames = names.stream()
    .filter(name -> name.length() > 3)
    .map(String::toUpperCase)
    .collect(java.util.stream.Collectors.toList());
```

Streams are expressive and composable — but they have a learning curve. We'll cover them fully in Module 9. For now, recognize the pattern when you see it and know that `list.stream()` starts a pipeline.

